          "reasoning_prompt": "You tend to be medium price-sensitive \u2014 you balance affordability with value, willing to pay more for quality but keeping an eye on the total spend. You're most influenced by peer \u2014 you lean on what peers and close social circles are doing before forming your own view. You tend to weigh options before switching. Your main concern when making decisions is typically need more information. You often feel the tension between Aspires to more than current constraints allow."
        },
        "narrative": {
          "first_person": "I do my own math first. Always. It's a habit from my scholarship days in Pune \u2014 when every rupee had to justify itself twice over \u2014 and honestly, that instinct hasn't left me even now that we're both earning well. I'll hear what my friends in the building are doing, which school they picked, which mutual fund they moved into, and I'll note it. Their choices matter to me. But I still go home and run the numbers myself before I decide anything.\n\nThe tension I live with is real \u2014 I want more for us, a bigger flat, better holidays, Arya's education sorted early \u2014 but I'm not willing to stretch recklessly. Price isn't about being cheap. It's about being honest with myself about what this decision actually costs, and whether I trust it enough to own it completely.",
          "third_person": "Priya Sharma is a 34-year-old postgraduate professional navigating early family life in Mumbai with a dual income and persistent financial vigilance shaped long before her current stability. Her scholarship years created a deeply internalized logic: price comes first, and her own calculations outrank external advice. This isn't mere frugality \u2014 it's a trust architecture built from necessity and reinforced through experience.\n\nWhat makes Priya analytically interesting is the tension between her aspirational self and her constrained decision-making habits. She earns enough to reach higher, yet her mental models haven't fully updated to reflect that reality. She researches extensively before committing, not because she lacks resources, but because she distrusts incomplete information and resists being sold to.\n\nHer social orientation (0.28) is moderate but meaningful \u2014 she observes peers closely, using their choices as soft validation before forming her own view. She isn't led by social proof; she triangulates with it. This combination of price-anchoring, self-trust, and peer-referencing creates a careful, deliberate consumer who moves slowly but decisively once her internal criteria are satisfied.",
          "display_name": "Priya"
        },
        "decision_bullets": [
          "Decision style: social (score 0.28)",
          "Primary value driver: price",
