        "narrative": {
          "first_person": "I want the good life \u2014 I see it clearly. Better apartment, family trips, maybe a car upgrade. But I've been burned before. A few years ago I miscalculated an EMI commitment and spent eight months eating into savings I couldn't afford to touch. That taught me something permanent: numbers don't lie, excitement does.\n\nSo now I run every purchase through a hard filter. What's the actual cost? What am I giving up? I'll ask two or three people I trust what they paid, what worked, what didn't. Not because I can't decide alone \u2014 I can \u2014 but because real-world experience cuts through the marketing noise faster than any brochure.\n\nThe tension is real. I'm 32, I have a family, and I want more than my current income comfortably allows. But I won't let aspiration override arithmetic. Not again.",
          "third_person": "Siddharth Iyer is a 32-year-old postgraduate professional in Hyderabad navigating the quiet friction between where he is and where he wants to be. Supporting a nuclear household of three on a middle income, he operates with a financial vigilance shaped by a formative misstep \u2014 an EMI commitment that exceeded his actual capacity, leaving him with a disciplined, almost hypervigilant approach to cost evaluation.\n\nThis experience explains why price functions not merely as a preference but as a primary decision filter. Before any significant purchase, Siddharth runs detailed internal cost calculations, mentally stress-testing affordability before allowing aspiration to enter the equation. His trust anchor is himself, reflecting a self-reliance born from having been let down by optimistic assumptions.\n\nYet he is not purely autonomous. His moderately social decision style means peer behavior serves as a reference signal \u2014 he watches what his circle does, using their choices to calibrate his own without fully outsourcing judgment. This combination produces a careful, comparison-heavy consumer who is genuinely aspirational but structurally cautious, perpetually negotiating between the life he imagines and the budget he respects.",
          "display_name": "Siddharth"
        },
        "decision_bullets": [
          "Decision style: social (score 0.28)",
          "Primary value driver: price",
          "Risk appetite: medium",
          "Objection (high likelihood, friction): price vs value",
          "Tension: Aspires to more than current constraints allow"
        ],
