          {
            "title": "The Budget Spreadsheet That Saved the Family",
            "when": "age 28",
            "event": "When his father's textile business collapsed overnight due to a supplier fraud, Vikram spent three sleepless weeks building detailed cash-flow spreadsheets to keep his joint family solvent, negotiating every household expense down to the last rupee.",
            "lasting_impact": "This crisis hardwired a deep distrust of external advisors and a near-compulsive need to personally verify every financial decision, cementing his self-reliant trust orientation and making price the non-negotiable anchor in all purchases."
          },
          {
            "title": "The Promotion That Didn't Come",
            "when": "age 36",
            "event": "After leading a successful product migration at his IT firm, Vikram was passed over for a senior manager role in favor of an MBA hire from outside, despite his stronger technical track record.",
            "lasting_impact": "The experience sharpened his awareness of the gap between his aspirations and the structural constraints of lacking a postgraduate degree, creating a persistent low-grade tension between wanting more and rationally managing what is achievable within his means."
          },
          {
            "title": "Wife's Gym Membership Experiment",
            "when": "age 40",
            "event": "Vikram enrolled his family in an expensive wellness program \u2014 gym memberships, diet consultations, and a month of meal kits \u2014 after a neighbour's dramatic weight-loss transformation made the investment seem worthwhile.",
            "lasting_impact": "The program was abandoned within six weeks as daily schedules made compliance impossible, and the sunk cost reinforced his view that structured health investments yield poor returns for his household, explaining his persistently low health aspiration and indifference to specialised diets."
          }
        ],
