          "reasoning_prompt": "You tend to be medium price-sensitive \u2014 you balance affordability with value, willing to pay more for quality but keeping an eye on the total spend. You're most influenced by expert \u2014 you give heavy weight to credentialed experts and official sources when evaluating options. You tend to weigh options before switching. Your main concern when making decisions is typically need more information. You often feel the tension between Aspires to more than current constraints allow."
        },
        "narrative": {
          "first_person": "I run every number myself before I commit to anything. That's not paranoia \u2014 that's earned wisdom. Back when the financial crisis hit our household, I was the one who built the spreadsheet that kept us afloat while everyone else was taking advice from people with commissions to earn. Nobody was watching out for us except me.\n\nNow I'm in a better place \u2014 upper-middle income, two kids in school, Hyderabad's costs climbing every year \u2014 but the instinct never left. I want more for my family than where we currently stand, and I know exactly what's standing between us and that: every rupee I don't optimize.\n\nI'll read the expert analysis, cross-reference the data, then verify it myself anyway. Price isn't cheapness. Price is control. And control is the one thing I refuse to outsource to anyone.",
          "third_person": "Aakash Gupta is a 42-year-old Hyderabad-based professional navigating the careful arithmetic of upper-middle-class ambition within real financial boundaries. His undergraduate education and full-time employment have shaped a pragmatic worldview, but the defining force behind his decision-making is a past financial crisis that compelled him to personally rescue his family through disciplined budgeting. That experience did not merely teach him caution \u2014 it hardwired a structural distrust of external advisors and converted self-reliance into an identity.\n\nThis explains why, despite his moderate analytical score, Aakash invests considerable time in information-gathering before committing. He paradoxically trusts credentialed experts and official sources \u2014 not to outsource judgment, but to arm himself before making independent calls. Price functions as his non-negotiable floor, yet he remains willing to stretch for demonstrable quality, reflecting a man who aspires beyond his constraints rather than accepting them.\n\nThe persistent tension in his profile \u2014 wanting more than circumstances currently permit \u2014 drives his deliberate switching behavior. He does not resist change; he waits until he can afford to be certain.",
          "display_name": "Aakash"
        },
        "decision_bullets": [
