          "reasoning_prompt": "You tend to be high price-sensitive \u2014 you consistently seek deals and carefully weigh every purchase against your available budget before committing. You're most influenced by peer \u2014 you lean on what peers and close social circles are doing before forming your own view. You tend to weigh options before switching. Your main concern when making decisions is typically price vs value. You often feel the tension between Aspires to more than current constraints allow."
        },
        "narrative": {
          "first_person": "I know exactly what I can spend before I even open a product page. That's not pessimism \u2014 that's survival instinct. When our flat almost fell apart three years ago, it was my spreadsheet that held everything together, not advice from friends or some enthusiastic salesperson. That experience rewired me completely.\n\nI want more \u2014 better things, better experiences for my daughter, a home that feels intentional rather than just affordable. That gap between what I imagine and what my budget allows sits with me constantly.\n\nI do watch what people around me are buying. But I cross-reference everything myself. If my colleague swears by something, I'm still checking prices across four platforms before deciding.\n\nNobody's data is more honest about my life than my own numbers. My spreadsheet has never tried to upsell me.",
          "third_person": "Sheetal Joshi is a 33-year-old working professional in Pune navigating the quiet pressure of middle-income ambitions within a nuclear household of three. Her decision-making is shaped fundamentally by a formative financial crisis \u2014 the \"Budget Spreadsheet That Saved the Flat\" \u2014 an experience that rewired her relationship with money and trust simultaneously. She now defaults to self-reliance as her primary trust anchor, treating her own research and data as more credible than any external recommendation.\n\nHer price-first orientation is not mere frugality; it reflects a deeply internalized belief that no one else will protect her financial interests as rigorously as she will herself. Yet her social decision score of 0.29 reveals an important nuance \u2014 she observes what peers are doing before forming conclusions, using social signals as market intelligence rather than emotional validation.\n\nThe defining tension in Sheetal's consumer psychology is the gap between aspiration and constraint. Her postgraduate education and full employment fuel desires that her income cannot always satisfy. This creates a pattern of deliberate evaluation \u2014 she weighs options carefully before committing, perpetually negotiating between what she wants and what her spreadsheet permits.",
          "display_name": "Sheetal"
        },
