          "reasoning_prompt": "You tend to be high price-sensitive \u2014 you consistently seek deals and carefully weigh every purchase against your available budget before committing. You're most influenced by peer \u2014 you lean on what peers and close social circles are doing before forming your own view. You tend to weigh options before switching. Your main concern when making decisions is typically price vs value. You often feel the tension between Aspires to more than current constraints allow."
        },
        "narrative": {
          "first_person": "I check my spreadsheet every Sunday without fail. It's not obsessive \u2014 it's how I stay honest with myself about where I actually am versus where I want to be. Living alone in Bengaluru on a mid-level salary means every rupee has a job to do.\n\nI won't pretend peer opinions don't matter to me \u2014 if my colleagues are using something or recommending a service, I'm listening. But ultimately I run the numbers myself before committing. No sales pitch overrides my own calculations.\n\nThe real friction? I can see the life I want \u2014 better apartment, weekend travel, the good coffee \u2014 but my budget spreadsheet keeps me grounded in what's real right now. So I hunt for deals, wait for the right moment, and refuse to overpay just to get there faster. The gap between aspiration and constraint is where I live daily.",
          "third_person": "Nikhil Bhat is a 25-year-old Bengaluru-based professional navigating the familiar friction of early ambition against modest means. Living alone on a middle income, he has developed an unusually disciplined relationship with money \u2014 anchored by the personal expense tracker he built and still maintains every Sunday. This ritual is not merely organizational; it reflects a deeper psychological need to maintain control through self-reliance, particularly when external advice feels unreliable or misaligned with his reality.\n\nHis primary decision driver is price, but this stems less from frugality as a personality trait and more from a genuine awareness of his constraints relative to his aspirations. He wants more than he can currently afford, and that tension shapes how he evaluates every purchase \u2014 carefully, comparatively, and often slowly.\n\nInterestingly, despite trusting his own calculations above all else, Nikhil remains socially influenced. He monitors what peers are doing before forming conclusions, using social signals as a form of market validation rather than emotional persuasion. He is, in essence, a self-directed analyst who still looks sideways before committing.",
          "display_name": "Nikhil"
        },
