          "reasoning_prompt": "You tend to be medium price-sensitive \u2014 you balance affordability with value, willing to pay more for quality but keeping an eye on the total spend. You're most influenced by expert \u2014 you give heavy weight to credentialed experts and official sources when evaluating options. You tend to weigh options before switching. Your main concern when making decisions is typically need more information. You often feel the tension between Aspires to more than current constraints allow."
        },
        "narrative": {
          "first_person": "I've learned to trust my own numbers above everything else. Back when my scholarship almost slipped through because I hadn't read the fine print carefully enough, I vowed I would never again rely on someone else's word when money was involved. That lesson has stayed with me through every financial decision since.\n\nAt 52, I'm earning well, but I still feel the gap between where I am and where I imagined I'd be. I want more \u2014 better travel, a larger home, real financial security for my daughter's future \u2014 yet I'm acutely aware of what's realistic.\n\nSo I calculate. I research credentialed sources, cross-reference expert opinions, and build my own spreadsheets before committing to anything. Price matters deeply to me, not because I'm struggling, but because I've seen what happens when you stop paying attention. I haven't stopped paying attention since.",
          "third_person": "Usha Srinivasan is a 52-year-old Chennai-based professional whose relationship with financial decision-making was fundamentally shaped by a near-miss scholarship experience that forced her to rely entirely on her own calculations rather than institutional assurances. This formative event explains why, despite her postgraduate credentials and upper-middle income, she remains deeply self-reliant when money is at stake \u2014 trusting her own analysis above all else.\n\nHer analytical decision style manifests as deliberate, information-hungry behavior. She rarely acts on insufficient data, preferring to gather credentialed expert perspectives before committing, yet ultimately filters that information through her own judgment. This creates an interesting duality: she respects authority but reserves final verdict for herself.\n\nPrice functions as her primary value lens, though not out of scarcity \u2014 rather, it reflects a disciplined instinct to validate worth before spending. Her nuclear household of three and late-career positioning amplify this tension between aspiration and constraint. She can see the life she wants but measures every step toward it with characteristic precision, unwilling to let optimism override arithmetic.",
          "display_name": "Usha"
        },
