  "sarvam_enrichment": [
    {
      "enrichment_applied": true,
      "enrichment_provider": "sarvam",
      "enrichment_scope": "narrative_and_examples",
      "persona_id": "pg-pg-001",
      "enriched_narrative": {
        "first_person": "I run the numbers before I run my feelings. Every purchase gets the same treatment \u2014 I open three tabs, check the unit cost on 1mg or Amazon, look for a coupon code, then sit with it. My internship days trained me hard: I was splitting rent in Pune on a stipend that barely covered groceries, calculating price-per-gram on dal packets at D-Mart. That discipline never left.\n\nNow I earn better, but the habit stays. I want the good things \u2014 the better apartment in HSR Layout, the premium tools, the upgrade \u2014 and I can genuinely see myself getting there. But right now, every rupee has to justify itself. I don't impulse-buy. I compare. I wait.\n\nThe tension is real: I aspire upward but I budget downward. I trust my own spreadsheet more than any salesperson's pitch.",
        "third_person": "Arjun Menon is a 29-year-old Bengaluru-based professional navigating the gap between postgraduate ambitions and a middle-income reality. Living alone in a 1BHK across Koramangala or HSR Layout, he carries the financial discipline forged during lean internship years in Pune, when tracking unit costs at D-Mart became survival strategy rather than habit. That formative reckoning hardwired a price-first decision framework that now governs purchases across every category, from groceries to SaaS subscriptions sourced through Amazon or 1mg.\n\nHis analytical decision style \u2014 moderate rather than exhaustive \u2014 means he researches deliberately but stops short of paralysis. He compares, calculates, and only commits when value is demonstrably justified against cost. Because he trusts his own judgment above external validation, peer recommendations carry limited weight, yet advertising reaches him effectively when framed in rational, value-oriented terms aligned with his internal evaluation criteria.\n\nThe deeper driver is aspiration constrained by circumstance. Arjun wants more than his current budget permits, creating persistent tension that makes switching decisions slow and deliberate \u2014 he cannot afford mistakes. Every purchase is quietly a negotiation between who he is today and who he intends to become."
      },
      "cultural_references_added": [
        "D-Mart (mid-range hypermarket chain, standard urban Indian reference)",
        "1mg (e-pharmacy platform, aligns with price-sensitive digital consumer)",
        "Amazon (primary e-commerce habit for Bengaluru metro professionals)",
