    {
      "enrichment_applied": true,
      "enrichment_provider": "sarvam",
      "enrichment_scope": "narrative_and_examples",
      "persona_id": "pg-pg-002",
      "enriched_narrative": {
        "first_person": "I do my own math first. Always. It's a habit from my scholarship days at a Mumbai university \u2014 when every rupee had to justify itself twice over in a spreadsheet I built myself \u2014 and honestly, that instinct hasn't left me even now that we're both earning well. I'll hear what my friends in the Powai towers are doing, which school they picked, which mutual fund they moved into, and I'll note it. Their choices matter to me. But I still go home and run the numbers myself before I decide anything.\n\nThe tension I live with is real \u2014 I want more for us, a bigger flat in Bandra or Worli, better holidays, Arya's education sorted early \u2014 but I'm not willing to stretch recklessly. Price isn't about being cheap. It's about being honest with myself about what this decision actually costs, and whether I trust it enough to own it completely.",
        "third_person": "Priya Sharma is a 34-year-old postgraduate professional navigating early family life in Mumbai's upper-middle-class neighborhoods with a dual income and persistent financial vigilance shaped long before her current stability. Her scholarship years in a Mumbai university created a deeply internalized logic: price comes first, and her own spreadsheet-driven calculations outrank external advice. This isn't mere frugality \u2014 it's a trust architecture built from necessity and reinforced through the 24-month savings discipline that kept her anchored during the Powai flat decision at 31.\n\nWhat makes Priya analytically interesting is the tension between her aspirational self and her measured decision-making habits. She earns enough to reach higher, yet her mental models haven't fully updated to reflect that reality. She researches extensively before committing, not because she lacks resources, but because she distrusts incomplete information and resists being sold to. Her social orientation is moderate but meaningful \u2014 she observes peers in her building closely, using their school and fund choices as soft validation before forming her own view. This combination of price-anchoring, self-trust, and peer-referencing creates a careful, deliberate consumer who moves slowly but decisively once her internal criteria are satisfied."
      },
      "cultural_references_added": [
        "Mumbai university (location-specific institution)",
        "Powai towers (neighborhood in Mumbai, upper-middle-class locality)",
        "Bandra or Worli (aspirational Mumbai neighborhoods)",
        "spreadsheet-driven approach (traces to life_story age 22)",
        "24-month savings discipline (traces to life_story age 31)"
      ],
      "contextual_examples_replaced": [
        {
          "original": "a supermarket",
          "replacement": "N/A \u2014 no supermarket reference in original",
          "attribute_source": "location.city"
        },
