    {
      "enrichment_applied": true,
      "enrichment_provider": "sarvam",
      "enrichment_scope": "narrative_and_examples",
      "persona_id": "pg-pg-003",
      "enriched_narrative": {
        "first_person": "I still remember surviving on that \u20b98,000 stipend \u2014 every rupee tracked in a color-coded spreadsheet on Google Sheets, every 'treat' justified against the monthly balance. That discipline didn't leave when the salary came in. It just got quieter.\n\nNow I'm earning decently, but Chennai isn't cheap, and living alone in Velachery means every expense lands entirely on me. I want the good version of things \u2014 the better phone, the upgraded plan \u2014 but I can't ignore the math. So I cross-check 91mobiles and Flipkart, scroll through r/india threads, ask peers what they actually paid before I commit to anything.\n\nThe gap between what I want and what I'll let myself spend is real. I don't call it being cheap. I call it being honest about where I am right now \u2014 and strategic about where I'm going. Price isn't a limitation. It's my discipline.",
        "third_person": "Karthik Rajan is a 27-year-old Chennai-based software analyst whose decision-making architecture was fundamentally shaped by years of managing on a tight \u20b98,000 monthly postgraduate stipend at Anna University. Living alone in Velachery on a middle income, he approaches purchases with the methodical precision of someone who has learned, through necessity, that financial mistakes have real consequences. His analytical orientation \u2014 evidenced by his habit of comparing 91mobiles, Flipkart, and Amazon reviews, then cross-referencing peer prices on WhatsApp circles \u2014 is not mere frugality but a deeply internalized survival strategy.\n\nWhat makes Karthik psychologically interesting is the tension at his core: he aspires to a lifestyle that currently outpaces his resources, yet his price-first framework keeps those aspirations in check. He trusts his own judgment above all external authorities, yet paradoxically monitors peer behavior closely through social circles before forming opinions. His switching threshold is high; inertia protects him from impulsive decisions. Every purchase becomes a negotiation between who he is today and who he intends to become \u2014 with price consistently winning that argument."
      },
      "cultural_references_added": [
        "\u20b98,000 monthly stipend (historical anchor)",
