    {
      "enrichment_applied": true,
      "enrichment_provider": "sarvam",
      "enrichment_scope": "narrative_and_examples",
      "persona_id": "pg-pg-004",
      "enriched_narrative": {
        "first_person": "I run the numbers before I run on instinct. Every financial decision I make goes through a mental audit \u2014 I learned that lesson the hard way when a Delhi University fellowship I'd counted on fell apart because I'd trusted the department's word instead of reading the fine print myself. Never again.\n\nLiving in Dwarka with two kids and a household to manage on one combined income that sounds comfortable but stretches thin against real ambitions \u2014 I feel that gap constantly. I want more for us than what the budget currently permits, and that tension doesn't go away.\n\nSo I research obsessively. I read Amazon reviews and IndiaStack community forums, cross-check BigBasket unit prices against D-Mart, compare total cost of ownership \u2014 not just sticker price. I'm not cheap, I'm precise. I'll pay for quality, but I need to justify every rupee. Nobody validates my decisions but me.",
        "third_person": "Nisha Agarwal is a 38-year-old Delhi-based professional whose financial decision-making is shaped profoundly by a formative experience with institutional betrayal. Having navigated a scholarship audit at Delhi University that exposed the unreliability of external authorities, she emerged with a deeply self-reliant trust orientation \u2014 she verifies everything personally before committing, treating institutional claims with measured skepticism.\n\nHer analytical decision style manifests as deliberate information-gathering before any significant purchase or financial choice. While price is her primary anchor \u2014 honed during her EMI-heavy years in Dwarka \u2014 she is not rigidly budget-driven. She will pay a premium when evidence justifies it, but she must construct that justification herself through spreadsheet modeling and unit-price comparison across retail platforms.\n\nOnline ecosystems like Amazon reviews and housing community forums serve as her preferred validation layer, functioning as a substitute for institutional trust she no longer extends freely. She treats peer consensus as credible data rather than mere opinion. The core tension animating her behavior is the gap between her aspirations and her current constraints."
      },
      "cultural_references_added": [
        "Delhi University (life story location specificity)",
        "Dwarka (residential location, EMI context)",
        "Amazon reviews (upper-middle metro shopping behavior)",
        "BigBasket (urban grocery platform, unit-price comparison habit)",
        "D-Mart (hypermarket chain, Delhi metro prevalence)",
        "IndiaStack community forums (Delhi metro online communities)"
      ],
      "contextual_examples_replaced": [
        {
          "original": "a scholarship I'd counted on fell apart",
          "replacement": "a Delhi University fellowship I'd counted on fell apart",
          "attribute_source": "education + life_story.age_24"
