    {
      "enrichment_applied": true,
      "enrichment_provider": "sarvam",
      "enrichment_scope": "narrative_and_examples",
      "persona_id": "pg-pg-005",
      "enriched_narrative": {
        "first_person": "I want the good life \u2014 I see it clearly. Better apartment in a gated community, family trips to Ooty, maybe a car upgrade. But I've been burned before. A few years ago I miscalculated an EMI commitment and spent eight months eating into savings I couldn't afford to touch. That taught me something permanent: numbers don't lie, excitement does.\n\nSo now I run every purchase through a hard filter. What's the actual cost? What am I giving up? I'll ask two or three people I trust what they paid, what worked, what didn't \u2014 my colleagues at work, neighbors in Kondapur, maybe someone from my MBA cohort. Not because I can't decide alone \u2014 I can \u2014 but because real-world experience cuts through the marketing noise faster than any brochure.\n\nThe tension is real. I'm 32, I have a family, and I want more than my current income comfortably allows. But I won't let aspiration override arithmetic. Not again.",
        "third_person": "Siddharth Iyer is a 32-year-old postgraduate professional in Hyderabad navigating the quiet friction between where he is and where he wants to be. Supporting a nuclear household of three on a middle income, he operates with a financial vigilance shaped by a formative misstep \u2014 an EMI commitment that exceeded his actual capacity, leaving him with a disciplined, almost hypervigilant approach to cost evaluation.\n\nThis experience explains why price functions not merely as a preference but as a primary decision filter. Before any significant purchase \u2014 whether a flat lease in Kondapur or appliances from Vijayashankar or Croma \u2014 Siddharth runs detailed internal cost calculations, mentally stress-testing affordability against his spreadsheet logic before allowing aspiration to enter the equation. His trust anchor is himself, reflecting a self-reliance born from having been let down by optimistic assumptions during his data analytics thesis.\n\nYet he is not purely autonomous. His moderately social decision style means peer behavior serves as a reference signal \u2014 he watches what his circle does, consulting colleagues and neighbors to calibrate choices without fully outsourcing judgment. This combination produces a careful, comparison-heavy consumer who is genuinely aspirational but structurally cautious, perpetually negotiating between the life he imagines and the budget he respects."
      },
      "cultural_references_added": [
        "Ooty (regional weekend destination preference for middle-income Hyderabad families)",
        "Kondapur (specific locality where he lives \u2014 traces to life story: flat search)",
        "MBA cohort (peer reference source \u2014 traces to postgraduate education)",
        "Vijayashankar (Telangana-based appliance retailer, middle-income accessible)",
        "Croma (metro retail chain, accessible in Hyderabad, middle-income electronics purchase point)"
      ],
      "contextual_examples_replaced": [
