    {
      "enrichment_applied": true,
      "enrichment_provider": "sarvam",
      "enrichment_scope": "narrative_and_examples",
      "persona_id": "pg-pg-012",
      "enriched_narrative": {
        "first_person": "I know exactly what I can spend before I even open a product page. That's not pessimism \u2014 it's survival instinct. When our flat almost fell apart three years ago, it was my spreadsheet that held everything together, not advice from friends or some enthusiastic salesman at a Pune showroom. That experience rewired me completely.\n\nI want more \u2014 better things, better experiences for my son Aryan, a home that feels intentional rather than just affordable. That gap between what I imagine and what my budget allows sits with me constantly.\n\nI do watch what people around me are buying. But I cross-reference everything myself \u2014 checking prices on Amazon, Flipkart, and local D-Mart before deciding. If my colleague swears by something, I'm still verifying it against my own data.\n\nNobody's data is more honest about my life than my own numbers. My spreadsheet has never tried to upsell me.",
        "third_person": "Sheetal Joshi is a 33-year-old senior analyst in Pune navigating the quiet pressure of middle-income ambitions within a nuclear household of three. Her decision-making is shaped fundamentally by a formative financial crisis \u2014 the \"Budget Spreadsheet That Saved the Flat\" \u2014 an experience that rewired her relationship with money and trust simultaneously. She now defaults to self-reliance as her primary trust anchor, treating her own research and price comparisons across Amazon, Flipkart, and D-Mart as more credible than any external recommendation.\n\nHer price-first orientation is not mere frugality; it reflects a deeply internalized belief that no one else will protect her financial interests as rigorously as she will herself. Yet her social decision score of 0.29 reveals an important nuance \u2014 she observes what peers in her Pune professional circle are doing before forming conclusions, using social signals as market intelligence rather than emotional validation.\n\nThe defining tension in Sheetal's consumer psychology is the gap between aspiration and constraint. Her postgraduate education and full employment at a Pune-based firm fuel desires that her income cannot always satisfy. This creates a pattern of deliberate evaluation \u2014 she weighs options carefully before committing, perpetually negotiating between what she wants and what her spreadsheet permits."
      },
      "cultural_references_added": [
        "D-Mart (Pune-based retail chain, accessible to middle-income households)",
        "Amazon/Flipkart (primary price-comparison platforms used by metro professionals)",
        "Pune showroom (location-specific retail context)",
        "Aryan (son's name, already in life story; retained for authenticity)"
      ],
      "contextual_examples_replaced": [
