    {
      "enrichment_applied": true,
      "enrichment_provider": "sarvam",
      "enrichment_scope": "narrative_and_examples",
      "persona_id": "pg-pg-013",
      "enriched_narrative": {
        "first_person": "I check my spreadsheet every Sunday without fail. It's not obsessive \u2014 it's how I stay honest with myself about where I actually am versus where I want to be. Living alone in Bengaluru on a mid-level salary means every rupee has a job to do.\n\nI won't pretend peer opinions don't matter to me \u2014 if my colleagues are using something or recommending a service, I'm listening. But ultimately I run the numbers myself before committing. No sales pitch overrides my own calculations.\n\nThe real friction? I can see the life I want \u2014 a better apartment in Indiranagar, weekend trips on MakeMyTrip, the good coffee at Third Wave \u2014 but my budget spreadsheet keeps me grounded in what's real right now. So I hunt for deals on Cred cashback, wait for the right moment, and refuse to overpay just to get there faster. The gap between aspiration and constraint is where I live daily.",
        "third_person": "Nikhil Bhat is a 25-year-old Bengaluru-based professional navigating the familiar friction of early ambition against modest means. Living alone on a middle income in a PG or rented apartment, he has developed an unusually disciplined relationship with money \u2014 anchored by the personal expense tracker he built and still maintains every Sunday, often cross-checking against his HDFC or ICICI bank app alerts. This ritual reflects a deeper psychological need to maintain control through self-reliance, particularly when external advice feels unreliable.\n\nHis primary decision driver is price, but this stems less from frugality as a personality trait and more from genuine awareness of his constraints relative to his aspirations. He wants more than he can currently afford, and that tension shapes every purchase evaluation. Interestingly, despite trusting his own calculations above all else, Nikhil remains socially influenced \u2014 monitoring what peers are doing on LinkedIn or during Slack conversations before forming conclusions, using social signals as market validation rather than emotional persuasion. He is, in essence, a self-directed analyst who still looks sideways before committing."
      },
      "cultural_references_added": [
