    {
      "enrichment_applied": true,
      "enrichment_provider": "sarvam",
      "enrichment_scope": "narrative_and_examples",
      "persona_id": "pg-pg-017",
      "enriched_narrative": {
        "first_person": "I've spent thirty years running numbers in my head before anyone else even picks up a calculator. That textile firm accounts crisis \u2014 when everyone trusted the wrong vendor invoices and we nearly lost everything \u2014 taught me something I've never forgotten: verify everything yourself, trust no one else's math.\n\nI want better things for my family of five in this joint household. I see what others have in South Delhi and I know we deserve it too. But I won't stretch foolishly. Every purchase gets weighed \u2014 what does this actually cost me, what do I genuinely get back?\n\nI stick with brands I know. Not ICICI or HDFC blindly, but the ones that have already passed my scrutiny. Chasing unknown discounts is how people get burned.\n\nThe tension is real though. My aspirations sit slightly ahead of my wallet. I'm always calculating the gap, looking for the honest deal that closes it.",
        "third_person": "Raghav Pandey is a 55-year-old Delhi professional navigating the final stretch of a working life shaped by hard-won caution. Managing a joint household of five on a middle income, he carries the weight of collective financial responsibility with practiced discipline. His moderately analytical decision style is not merely temperamental \u2014 it was forged through the vendor-invoice crisis at his textile firm, cementing a trust orientation that runs firmly inward. He verifies ledger entries before he commits, and he rarely commits quickly.\n\nPrice sensitivity is his dominant behavioral driver, but it operates alongside strong loyalty to established brands \u2014 Videocon, LG, familiar Delhi retailers \u2014 that function as cognitive shortcuts. These brands reduce the perceived risk where raw price comparisons cannot. This combination means Raghav is not simply a bargain hunter at D-Mart; he is a value validator, cross-referencing cost against credibility before moving forward.\n\nThe quieter force shaping his choices is aspiration constrained by the housing-loan setback in Rohini. He wants more than his middle-income budget comfortably allows, and that gap between desire and capacity keeps every purchasing decision slightly tense, deliberate, and personal."
      },
      "cultural_references_added": [
