    {
      "enrichment_applied": true,
      "enrichment_provider": "sarvam",
      "enrichment_scope": "narrative_and_examples",
      "persona_id": "pg-pg-018",
      "enriched_narrative": {
        "first_person": "I've learned to trust my own numbers above everything else. Back when my Anna University scholarship almost slipped through because I hadn't read the fine print carefully enough, I vowed I would never again rely on someone else's word when money was involved. That lesson has stayed with me through every financial decision since.\n\nAt 52, I'm earning well, but I still feel the gap between where I am and where I imagined I'd be. I want more \u2014 better travel, a larger home in Adyar or beyond, real financial security for my daughter's future \u2014 yet I'm acutely aware of what's realistic.\n\nSo I calculate. I cross-reference expert opinions from The Hindu's analysis or ICRA reports, build my own spreadsheets before committing to anything. Price matters deeply to me, not because I'm struggling, but because I've seen what happens when you stop paying attention. I haven't stopped paying attention since.",
        "third_person": "Usha Srinivasan is a 52-year-old Chennai-based professional whose relationship with financial decision-making was fundamentally shaped by a near-miss merit scholarship at Anna University that forced her to rely entirely on her own calculations rather than institutional assurances. This formative event explains why, despite her postgraduate credentials and upper-middle income, she remains deeply self-reliant when money is at stake \u2014 trusting her own analysis above credentialed reassurance.\n\nHer analytical decision style manifests as deliberate, information-hungry behavior. She gathers perspectives from credentialed expert sources \u2014 Hindu Business Line, ICRA ratings, or consulting firm analyses \u2014 before committing, yet ultimately filters that information through her own meticulous judgment. This creates an interesting duality: she respects institutional authority but reserves final verdict for herself.\n\nPrice functions as her primary value lens, though not out of scarcity \u2014 rather, it reflects a disciplined instinct to validate worth before spending. Her nuclear household of three in Adyar and late-career positioning amplify this tension between aspiration and constraint. She can see the life she wants but measures every step toward it with characteristic precision, unwilling to let optimism override arithmetic."
      },
      "cultural_references_added": [
        "Anna University",
        "Adyar",
        "The Hindu",
        "Hindu Business Line",
        "ICRA reports"
      ],
      "contextual_examples_replaced": [
        {
          "original": "a scholarship almost slipped through",
          "replacement": "my Anna University scholarship almost slipped through",
